column1: On 1 August 2019, will the upper limit of the Federal Reserve's target range for the federal funds rate be higher, the same, or lower than it was on 31 January 2019?
column6: ['Finance']
column11: The U.S. federal funds rate is the interest rate charged for overnight lending among financial institutions with accounts at the Federal Reserve and sets the base rate for borrowing costs across the financial system (Investopedia, The Federal Reserve). The upper limit of the range, set by the Federal Open Market Committee, was 2.5% at the end of the trading day on 31 January 2019 (The Federal Reserve, The Federal Reserve).

An FOMC meeting just ended. There was no consideration of raising the target range. All of the debate centered around the slowing of the economy and the need to preempt a further decrease in inflation. In March the FOMC stated a change would not occur for the rest of the year. At the end of this meeting, the FOMC voted unanimously to keep the rate where it is. There has been a decrease in consumer spending and investment. The housing marking has declined for five consecutive quarters. Moreover, the CORE rate of inflation is at 1.6 percent. At least one member of the fed, President Charlie Evans of Chicago, has said that if it falls to 1.5 percent, the fed should consider lowering the rate.

There are four federal open market committee meetings until August. [1] Latest Fed meeting set a dovish tone suggesting low likelihood of future raises. The market consensus also points toward no further raises. [1]. A decrease would be very unlikely as the Fed has been trying to cool the economy down, not the other way around. For the Fed to change its tack, there would have to be a significant turn for the worse for the US economy (beyond any concerns that made the Fed slow down its tightening in January).

Following the rate increases last year and Chairman Powell's comments on further rate increases in January, I think the most likely outcome is the Fed maintains the same rate until August. Not going 100% because there is always the possibility that inflation could tick up and they would have to raise rates to compensate.

Until the last Fed meetign most economists expected a few more steps over the course of the year, but the Fed has become clelarly more dovish. Actually, the signs that the US economy has crossed the peak and will cool down are increasing. Moreover, inflation is low so there is no need to hike the rated. However, the US economy is still growing and unemployment is low and, moreover, the Fed might want to show that the Trump government has no impact on its decisions, so the chance that the Fed will increase the Fed funds rate is clearly above zero.

A lower rate would feed cheap money into a system that does not need it: rates are already historically low and this would add gas to the balloon. A higher rate would be very unpopular in the White House, but would have an economic justification to take some of the fizz out of speculation. It would also be high in global terms and so attractive to foreign investors (I'd love to get 3% on some TIPS). However, that would strengthen the dollar, at a time when imports of basic materials are likely to get more expensive anyway (tariffs) and exports are looking for new markets (soybeans etc). The least-worst is to keep it the same, but there's a period in the year I've nicknamed 'the guns of August' when weird stuff can happen, so will revisit this later.
Leading indicators show policy rate lower into ~Q4'19. They'll probably bring rates back up again in H1'20, assuming political-financial-economic crisis abates.

The US economy is strong, it is very hard to see it reverting and start destroying jobs or with low expected inflation. The options market is pricing 2,3% chance of hike and 0,5% chance of cut, my guess its US economy is strong enough to justify a higher odds of another hiking.

Cannot remove policy tool by taking it lower; cut off option value and taking higher will put pressure on existing debt levels particularly on the national debt and could also cause a crowding out of other investments, particularly equities pushing valuation multiples down accordingly.
Economy is not likely to be growing faster. The Fed just decided to slow down a bit, so chances are slim they will change the target rate.
